The $500-an-Hour Monopoly Is Panicking

AI was supposed to widen access to justice. Instead, the system is trying to sort who gets to use it safely.

There is a new literacy test in law.

If you are wealthy enough to use AI inside a law firm, behind enterprise tools, under the cover of counsel, it is called innovation.

If you are poor enough to use a public AI tool because you cannot afford $500 an hour, it is called recklessness.

That is the emerging fault line of 2026.

It is not just about hallucinations. It is not just about ethics. It is not even just about privilege doctrine.

It is about who gets access to legal power.

Recent cases are starting to reveal the split. In United States v. Heppner, a federal court in the Southern District of New York held that certain materials generated with a public AI platform were protected by neither attorney-client privilege nor the work-product doctrine on the facts presented there. In Warner v. Gilbarco, by contrast, a federal court in Michigan treated a pro se litigant’s AI-assisted litigation preparation as protected work product. And in March 2026, Nippon Life sued OpenAI in Chicago, alleging unauthorized practice of law. These are not identical cases, but together they suggest that courts and institutions are drawing lines around AI use based on structure, supervision, and exposure.  ￼

That difference matters.

Because once ordinary people can use AI to decode procedure, organize facts, pressure-test strategy, and draft with discipline, the old monopoly on legal fluency starts to weaken.

Not disappear. Not collapse overnight.

But weaken enough to frighten the people who have long benefited from opacity.

The new class code

For years, the profession has framed legal knowledge as something too delicate, too technical, too dangerous to be distributed widely. The ordinary person was allowed forms, pamphlets, and slogans. Real procedural fluency remained expensive.

Now AI threatens to change that.

Not because a chatbot is a lawyer. It is not.

And not because every AI-generated filing is good. Many are not.

The threat is simpler: AI can help ordinary people learn faster than the gatekeepers expected.

It can explain standards. It can compare structures. It can surface missing arguments. It can help a litigant understand the difference between a timeline and a theory, between facts and admissible proof, between a grievance and a claim.

That is why the response has become so aggressive.

The public is told that AI is dangerous, and sometimes it is. But the danger is described very differently depending on who is using it.

When large firms use advanced tools behind institutional walls, the rhetoric becomes efficiency, innovation, competitiveness.

When a pro se litigant uses a public tool because they are broke, the rhetoric becomes irresponsibility, sanctions, waiver, and disorder.

That is not a neutral distinction. That is class coding.

The tool may be similar. The doctrine may be old. But the social meaning changes depending on whether the user has money, counsel, and infrastructure.

In other words: the same technology is being sorted into legitimate and illegitimate forms based less on its essence than on its setting.

Heppner and Warner are pointing at the same problem from opposite sides

The lesson of Heppner is not that all AI use destroys privilege. Commentary on the ruling has emphasized that the court applied existing privilege and work-product principles to the particular setup before it. The problem was exposure without the kind of protected legal relationship or litigation-preparation structure those doctrines typically require.  ￼

The lesson of Warner is not that all AI use is safe. It is that a court may view AI-assisted preparation differently when it sits inside a human-directed litigation workflow and functions as part of structured self-preparation. Both Proskauer and Kirkland describe Warner as charting a different path from Heppner on work-product protection.  ￼

Put differently, 2026 is producing a harsh divide:

Structure may be protected. Exposure may be punished.

That is a legal distinction.

But it is also an economic one.

Because sophisticated actors can buy structure.

Everyone else gets exposure.

The real battle is not over accuracy alone

That is why the Nippon Life lawsuit matters so much.

Reuters reports that Nippon Life accused OpenAI of unauthorized legal practice after ChatGPT allegedly encouraged a former disability claimant to reopen a settled dispute and file numerous papers. OpenAI called the allegations meritless and pointed to policy restrictions on legal advice. Whatever happens to the suit, the message is clear: the fight has escalated from “Can AI make mistakes?” to “Who gets to build and control legal guidance systems?”  ￼

That is a battle over jurisdiction.

A battle over professional territory.

A battle over who gets to translate legal complexity into usable public language.

And that matters because procedure is where a great deal of legal power lives. Procedure determines who gets heard, who gets dismissed, who preserves error, who misses a deadline, who knows what to ask for, and who loses without ever reaching the merits.

If AI helps ordinary people understand procedure, then AI is not just a writing aid. It is a power-shifting device.

That is the part the establishment fears most.

Most pro se litigants are not reckless. They are priced out.

This is the moral center that too many debates evade.

Most people do not go pro se because they worship self-representation. They go pro se because they cannot afford not to.

They are too poor for full representation, too complicated for generic forms, and too trapped by the stakes to walk away.

They are told the courthouse belongs to everyone.

Then they discover the language of access is rented by the hour.

This is why the current turn is so dangerous.

If AI becomes safe only for institutions, then it will not democratize law. It will simply upgrade the people who already have lawyers while disciplining the people who do not.

The wealthy will get protected workflows.

The poor will get warnings.

The firms will get copilots.

The public will get lectures.

That is not access to justice. That is hierarchy with better software.

The third category

There is, however, another possibility.

Not institutional AI.

Not chaotic consumer AI.

A third category: educational legal AI.

This is where I place the Legal Calculus Educational System.

The point is not to turn a chatbot into a lawyer.

The point is to turn the user into a strategist.

That means AI is not used as a vending machine for finished motions. It is used as part of a disciplined educational workflow. The human identifies the claims, the burdens, the chronology, the evidentiary gaps, the standard of review, the procedural posture. The AI helps map, compare, test, organize, and refine. Then another layer checks the draft. Then the human verifies the authorities and owns the reasoning.

That is not bot dependence.

That is assisted legal literacy.

And as the line between Heppner and Warner suggests, that distinction may matter more and more.

What a defensible workflow looks like

A serious public-interest AI workflow should have at least four features.

First, architecture before drafting.
Do not begin with “write my motion.” Begin with posture, timeline, elements, burdens, remedies, and proof.

Second, human authorship.
The user remains the decision-maker. AI assists; it does not substitute.

Third, multi-layer verification.
One system drafts, another checks, and the human verifies the citations, quotations, and procedural claims.

Fourth, privacy segmentation.
Do not dump privileged strategy, confidential facts, and public-facing prose into the same public prompt stream.

None of that eliminates risk.

But it changes the character of the work.

It moves the user from passive consumer to disciplined preparer.

It turns AI from a shortcut into a scaffold.

And it creates the kind of structure that courts may be more willing to respect.

The old model depends on scarcity

That is the larger political point.

The old legal order depends on scarcity of fluency.

It depends on a world where the average person does not know how to frame facts, preserve issues, identify procedural defects, or challenge a record. It depends on the ordinary litigant being overwhelmed before the merits are ever reached.

AI threatens that scarcity.

Not perfectly. Not automatically. Not without danger.

But enough to change the terrain.

So the system is doing what monopolies do when a new tool begins to erode their moat: it is trying to redefine unsanctioned use as illegitimate.

Not all of that pushback is cynical. Some of it is genuinely about quality and privacy.

But some of it is plainly about control.

Who gets the vault.

Who gets the shield.

Who gets called innovative.

Who gets called reckless.

The bottom line

The fight over AI in law is not really about whether a machine can draft a brief.

It is about whether ordinary people can acquire enough procedural literacy to stop being crushed by a system that prices fluency out of reach.

Heppner is a warning about exposure.
Warner is a signal that structure still matters.
Nippon Life shows the jurisdictional war is underway.  ￼

So the answer is not blind trust in AI.

And it is not panic.

It is disciplined, human-centered, educational use.

The old model depends on scarcity.

The next model should depend on literacy.

That is why the monopoly is panicking.

